    {
      "type": "grammar_spotlight",
      "content": "Look at 'naki-tsuru' (鳴きつる). Here, 'naki' is the action of the bird crying. By adding 'tsuru' (the attributive form of 'tsu'), the poet indicates the cry is *finished*. Because 'tsuru' is in the Rentaikei (Attributive form), it directly modifies the noun 'kata' (direction). \n\nLogic: [Crying] + [Finished] + [Direction] = 'The direction where the cry has finished/happened.' This creates a sharp temporal contrast: the sound is gone (tsu), but the moon remains.",
      "evidence": "See the poem above."
    },
